				<StackPanel Grid.Row="1">
					<TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
					<LineBreak/>
						<Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="24">
						III. PROBABILITY OF ESCALATION
						</Run>
						<LineBreak/>
						Given the current trajectory, hostilities are likely to escalate into more direct confrontations at sea.
						<LineBreak/>
						<LineBreak/>
						The Soviets may seek to demonstrate their resolve by conducting a controlled but aggressive naval engagement — possibly involving harassment of U.S. carrier groups or aggressive air intercepts.
						<LineBreak/>
						<LineBreak/>
						Any direct confrontation involving loss of life — particularly an attack on a capital ship — could prompt a broader regional conflict.
						<LineBreak/>
						<LineBreak/>
						<Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="24">
						IV. RECOMMENDATIONS
						</Run>
						<LineBreak/>
						1. Immediate transfer of U.S. 2nd Fleet forces in the Mediterranean to the North Atlantic (in progress).
						<LineBreak/>
						2. Deploy additional U.S. attack submarines to intercept and shadow Soviet SSBNs before they reach protected bastions.
						<LineBreak/>
						3. Coordinate with NATO allies to reinforce naval patrols and establish clear rules of engagement to prevent accidental escalation.
						<LineBreak/>
						4. Enhance diplomatic backchannels with Moscow to mitigate risks of miscalculation while maintaining a credible deterrent posture
						<LineBreak/>
						<LineBreak/>
						<Run FontWeight="Bold" FontSize="24">
						CONCLUSION
						</Run>
						<LineBreak/>
						Given rising tensions at sea and Moscow's pullback from the INF Treaty, there is a strong possibility that an escalation in hostilities could occur within the next 30-60 days. The United States and NATO must prepare for increased Soviet naval aggression while maintaining diplomatic efforts to prevent a full-scale confrontation.
					</TextBlock>
